subSection.paragraph:
Species of 

Adelosgryllus

, like many other phalangopsids, are nocturnal and can be found in humid forests, leaf litter, holes and crevices in the ground, under fallen logs, rodent burrows, termite mounds, caves, and some places close to urban areas (
Mesa & Zefa, 2004
; 
Gorochov, 2011
; 
Corrêa, 2017
; 

Corrêa 
et al.
, 2018

; 
Gorochov, 2019
; 

Merlo 
et al.
, 2021

).

All the species described in this work were collected in Brazil . The first species was collected in the caverna da Explosão Cave located in Xambioá municipality, Tocantins state , Northern Brazil ( Fig. 1 , white star). The cave is associated to metamorphosed limestones from the Xambioá formation (
Auler et al. , 2019
). Such region belongs to the Amazon Forest biome domain (
Olson et al. , 2001
).

The second species was collected on Pará state , municipality of Curionópolis, in SL-94, SL-109 and SL-110 caves ( Fig. 1 , black star) with additional specimens observed in SL-79, SL-82 and SL-121 caves, all inserted in the ferruginous region of Carajás. The predominant biome in the region is the Amazon Forest (
Olson et al. , 2001
).

